        title: "01 Introduction to Operating Systems", 
        readTime: 15, 
        content: "# Chapter 1: Introduction to Operating Systems\n\nAn **Operating System (OS)** is the most critical software on a computer. It acts as an intermediary between users and hardware, managing all resources efficiently.\n\n## What is an Operating System?\n\nAn OS provides a convenient environment for users to execute programs. It allocates resources (CPU, memory, I/O devices) to programs and ensures fair, secure access.\n\n### Key Functions of an OS:\n\n- **Process Management**: Creating, scheduling, suspending, resuming, and terminating processes.\n- **Memory Management**: Allocating and deallocating memory to processes, handling virtual memory.\n- **File System Management**: Creating, opening, reading, writing, deleting, and organizing files.\n- **I/O Device Management**: Managing device drivers and providing a uniform interface to hardware.\n- **Security & Protection**: Ensuring authorized access, user authentication, and data protection.\n- **Networking**: Managing network interfaces and protocol stacks.\n\n## Types of Operating Systems\n\n- **Batch OS**: Jobs grouped and processed sequentially. No user interaction during execution. Example: Old mainframes.\n- **Time-Sharing (Multitasking) OS**: CPU time is divided among multiple users/processes using time slices. Example: UNIX.\n- **Real-Time OS (RTOS)**: Guarantees response within strict time constraints. Used in missile systems, medical devices. Two types: Hard RTOS (deadlines are absolute) and Soft RTOS (deadlines are preferred).\n- **Distributed OS**: Multiple machines appear as a single system to the user.\n- **Embedded OS**: Designed for specific hardware with limited resources (e.g., IoT devices).\n\n## OS Architecture: Monolithic vs Microkernel\n\n- **Monolithic Kernel**: Entire OS runs in kernel space (Linux, UNIX). Fast but a single bug can crash the entire system.\n- **Microkernel**: Only essential services (IPC, scheduling) run in kernel space. File systems, drivers run in user space (Minix, QNX). More stable but slower due to IPC overhead.\n- **Hybrid Kernel**: Combines both approaches (Windows NT, macOS).\n\n## FAANG Interview Questions:\n- What is the difference between a process and a program?\n- Explain the difference between monolithic and microkernel architecture.\n- What are system calls? Give examples.\n- What is the boot process of an operating system?" 
