        title: "02 Kernels & System Calls", 
        readTime: 18, 
        content: "# Chapter 2: The Kernel and System Calls\n\nThe **Kernel** is the core of the operating system. It has complete control over everything in the system and is the first program loaded after the bootloader.\n\n## Dual-Mode Operation\n\nModern CPUs support at least two modes of operation:\n\n- **User Mode (Mode bit = 1)**: Restricted execution. Applications cannot directly access hardware or execute privileged instructions.\n- **Kernel Mode (Mode bit = 0)**: Full access to all hardware and instructions. The OS kernel runs in this mode.\n\n### Mode Switching:\n```\nUser Program → System Call → Trap → Kernel Mode → Execute Service → Return → User Mode\n```\n\nA **Trap** (or software interrupt) is triggered when a user program needs OS services. The CPU switches from User Mode to Kernel Mode, executes the requested service, and returns to User Mode.\n\n## System Calls\n\nSystem calls are the programmatic interface between a process and the OS kernel. They are the **only** way user programs can request kernel services.\n\n### Categories of System Calls:\n\n- **Process Control**: `fork()`, `exec()`, `exit()`, `wait()`, `kill()`\n- **File Management**: `open()`, `read()`, `write()`, `close()`, `lseek()`\n- **Device Management**: `ioctl()`, `read()`, `write()`\n- **Information Maintenance**: `getpid()`, `alarm()`, `sleep()`\n- **Communication**: `pipe()`, `shmget()`, `mmap()`, `socket()`\n\n### fork() Deep Dive (FAANG Favorite):\n```\nParent Process (PID=100)\n    |\n    fork()\n    |\n    +--------+--------+\n    |                 |\nParent (PID=100)  Child (PID=101)\nfork() returns 101  fork() returns 0\n```\n\n`fork()` creates an exact copy of the calling process. The parent gets the child's PID as return value, the child gets 0. This is how UNIX creates new processes.\n\n### How many processes does fork() in a loop create?\n```\nfor(int i = 0; i < 3; i++) fork();\n// Total processes = 2^3 = 8\n```\n\n## Interrupts vs Traps\n\n- **Interrupt**: Hardware-generated signal (keyboard press, disk I/O complete). Asynchronous.\n- **Trap**: Software-generated signal (system call, divide-by-zero). Synchronous.\n- **Both** cause the CPU to switch to Kernel Mode via the Interrupt Vector Table (IVT).\n\n## FAANG Interview Questions:\n- What happens when you type `ls` in a terminal? (Covers fork, exec, wait)\n- Difference between interrupt and trap?\n- What is the purpose of the mode bit?\n- Explain the fork() system call with examples." 
