        content: "# Chapter 3: Process Management\n\nA **Process** is a program in execution. It includes the program code, its current activity (PC, registers), a stack, a data section, and a heap.\n\n## Process vs Thread\n\n| Feature | Process | Thread |\n|---------|---------|--------|\n| Memory | Separate address space | Shares parent's address space |\n| Creation | Heavy (fork) | Lightweight (pthread_create) |\n| Communication | IPC (pipes, sockets) | Shared memory (direct) |\n| Context Switch | Expensive (~1-10μs) | Cheap (~0.1-1μs) |\n| Crash Impact | Isolated | Can crash entire process |\n\n## Process States & Lifecycle\n\n```\n              admit              dispatch\n  NEW ──────────> READY ──────────> RUNNING\n                   ^                  |\n                   |                  |\n            I/O complete        interrupt\n                   |                  |\n                   |    I/O or wait   v\n               WAITING <──────── RUNNING\n                                      |\n                                   exit\n                                      |\n                                      v\n                                 TERMINATED\n```\n\n**Key Transitions:**\n- **New → Ready**: Process admitted to ready queue by long-term scheduler.\n- **Ready → Running**: Short-term scheduler dispatches the process.\n- **Running → Waiting**: Process performs I/O or waits for an event.\n- **Running → Ready**: Time quantum expires (preemption) or higher-priority process arrives.\n- **Running → Terminated**: Process completes or is killed.\n\n## Process Control Block (PCB)\n\nThe PCB is the data structure the OS maintains for each process:\n\n- **Process ID (PID)**: Unique identifier.\n- **Process State**: NEW, READY, RUNNING, WAITING, TERMINATED.\n- **Program Counter (PC)**: Address of next instruction.\n- **CPU Registers**: Saved during context switch.\n- **Memory Management Info**: Page tables, segment tables.\n- **I/O Status**: List of open files, allocated devices.\n- **Scheduling Info**: Priority, CPU burst time.\n\n## Context Switch\n\nWhen the CPU switches from one process to another:\n1. Save the state (PCB) of the currently running process.\n2. Load the saved state (PCB) of the next process.\n3. Resume execution of the new process.\n\n**Cost**: Context switches are pure overhead (no useful work done). Typical time: 1-10 microseconds.\n\n## Inter-Process Communication (IPC)\n\n### Shared Memory:\n- Fast (no kernel involvement after setup).\n- Processes must synchronize access (risk of race conditions).\n\n### Message Passing:\n- Kernel manages communication.\n- Safer but slower due to system call overhead.\n- Types: Pipes, Message Queues, Sockets.\n\n### Pipes:\n```\nProcess A ──write──> [Pipe Buffer] ──read──> Process B\n```\n- **Named pipes (FIFO)**: Can be used between unrelated processes.\n- **Unnamed pipes**: Only between parent-child processes.\n\n## FAANG Interview Questions:\n- What is a zombie process? (Child terminated but parent hasn't called wait())\n- What is an orphan process? (Parent terminated before child)\n- Explain the difference between process and thread.\n- What happens during a context switch?" 
