        title: "04 CPU Scheduling Algorithms", 
        readTime: 25, 
        content: "# Chapter 4: CPU Scheduling Algorithms\n\nCPU Scheduling is the cornerstone of multiprogramming. The scheduler decides which process gets the CPU, when, and for how long.\n\n## Scheduling Criteria\n\n- **CPU Utilization**: Keep the CPU as busy as possible (ideal: 40-90%).\n- **Throughput**: Number of processes completed per unit time.\n- **Turnaround Time**: Total time from submission to completion.\n- **Waiting Time**: Time spent in the ready queue (key metric for comparison).\n- **Response Time**: Time from submission to first response (crucial for interactive systems).\n\n## Preemptive vs Non-Preemptive\n\n- **Non-Preemptive**: Once a process gets the CPU, it runs until it terminates or voluntarily yields (I/O wait).\n- **Preemptive**: The OS can forcibly take the CPU away (e.g., time quantum expires, higher-priority process arrives).\n\n## Algorithms Comparison\n\n### 1. FCFS (First Come First Served) — Non-Preemptive\n```\nProcess  Burst Time  Arrival Time\nP1       24          0\nP2       3           1\nP3       3           2\n\nGantt Chart: |  P1 (0-24)  |  P2 (24-27)  |  P3 (27-30)  |\nAvg Waiting Time = (0 + 23 + 25) / 3 = 16\n```\n**Problem**: Convoy Effect — short processes wait behind long ones.\n\n### 2. SJF (Shortest Job First) — Non-Preemptive\nSelects the process with the smallest CPU burst. **Provably optimal** for minimizing average waiting time.\n```\nProcess  Burst Time\nP1       6\nP2       8\nP3       2\nP4       4\n\nOrder: P3(2) → P4(4) → P1(6) → P2(8)\nAvg Waiting Time = (0 + 2 + 6 + 12) / 4 = 5\n```\n**Problem**: Starvation of long processes. Solution: **Aging** (gradually increase priority).\n\n### 3. SRTF (Shortest Remaining Time First) — Preemptive SJF\nIf a new process arrives with a shorter burst than the remaining time of the current process, preempt.\n\n### 4. Round Robin (RR) — Preemptive\nEach process gets a fixed **time quantum** (e.g., 4ms). After the quantum, it goes to the back of the ready queue.\n```\nTime Quantum = 4ms\nProcess  Burst Time\nP1       10\nP2       4\nP3       6\n\nGantt: |P1(0-4)|P2(4-8)|P3(8-12)|P1(12-16)|P3(16-18)|P1(18-20)|\n```\n**Trade-off**: Small quantum → more context switches (overhead). Large quantum → becomes FCFS.\n**Rule of thumb**: 80% of CPU bursts should be shorter than the quantum.\n\n### 5. Priority Scheduling\nEach process has a priority number. CPU allocated to highest-priority process.\n- **Problem**: Starvation (low-priority processes may never execute).\n- **Solution**: Aging (increase priority as wait time increases).\n\n### 6. Multilevel Queue Scheduling\nMultiple ready queues, each with its own scheduling algorithm:\n```\nQueue 1 (System processes):      RR, highest priority\nQueue 2 (Interactive processes): RR\nQueue 3 (Batch processes):       FCFS, lowest priority\n```\n\n### 7. Multilevel Feedback Queue\nProcesses can **move between queues** based on behavior:\n- CPU-bound process → pushed to lower-priority queue.\n- I/O-bound process → promoted to higher-priority queue.\n\n## FAANG Interview Questions:\n- Compare FCFS, SJF, and Round Robin with examples.\n- What is the Convoy Effect?\n- Calculate average waiting time for given processes.\n- What scheduling does Linux use? (CFS: Completely Fair Scheduler)" 
