        title: "06 Synchronization & Concurrency", 
        readTime: 25, 
        content: "# Chapter 6: Concurrency & Synchronization\n\nWhen multiple processes or threads access shared resources concurrently, we need synchronization to prevent data corruption.\n\n## Race Condition\n\nA race condition occurs when the result depends on the order of execution of concurrent operations.\n```\nThread A: count++    →    Read count (5) → Increment → Write (6)\nThread B: count++    →    Read count (5) → Increment → Write (6)\nExpected: 7, Actual: 6 (LOST UPDATE!)\n```\n\n## Critical Section Problem\n\nThe **Critical Section** is the code segment where shared resources are accessed. A solution must satisfy three conditions:\n\n1. **Mutual Exclusion**: Only one process can be in the critical section at a time.\n2. **Progress**: If no process is in the critical section, selection of the next process cannot be postponed indefinitely.\n3. **Bounded Waiting**: A limit must exist on the number of times other processes enter the critical section after a process has requested entry.\n\n## Synchronization Mechanisms\n\n### 1. Mutex (Mutual Exclusion Lock)\n```\nlock(mutex);\n// Critical Section\nunlock(mutex);\n```\nSimplest mechanism. Only the thread that locked can unlock. Binary (locked/unlocked).\n\n### 2. Semaphore\nA counter-based synchronization tool.\n- **Binary Semaphore** (0 or 1): Same as mutex.\n- **Counting Semaphore**: Value can be > 1 (controls access to a pool of resources).\n\n**Operations:**\n- `wait(S)` / `P(S)`: Decrement. If value < 0, block the process.\n- `signal(S)` / `V(S)`: Increment. If value <= 0, wake up a blocked process.\n\n### 3. Monitor\nA high-level synchronization construct (used in Java with `synchronized` keyword).\n- Only one thread can be active inside a monitor at a time.\n- Uses **condition variables** for waiting: `wait()`, `signal()`, `broadcast()`.\n\n## Classic Synchronization Problems (FAANG Favorites)\n\n### Producer-Consumer Problem:\n```\nBuffer[N] — shared bounded buffer\nmutex = 1, full = 0, empty = N\n\nProducer:                     Consumer:\n  wait(empty)                   wait(full)\n  wait(mutex)                   wait(mutex)\n  produce item to buffer        consume item from buffer\n  signal(mutex)                 signal(mutex)\n  signal(full)                  signal(empty)\n```\n\n### Dining Philosophers Problem:\n5 philosophers sit around a table. Each needs 2 forks to eat. If each picks up the left fork simultaneously → **Deadlock**.\n- **Solution**: Allow at most 4 philosophers to sit. Or use asymmetry (one philosopher picks right fork first).\n\n### Readers-Writers Problem:\n- Multiple readers can read simultaneously.\n- Only one writer at a time, and no readers while writing.\n- **First variant**: Readers preference (writers may starve).\n- **Second variant**: Writers preference (readers may starve).\n\n## FAANG Interview Questions:\n- What is a race condition? Give a real-world example.\n- Mutex vs Semaphore — when to use which?\n- Explain the Producer-Consumer problem with semaphores.\n- How does Java's synchronized keyword work internally?" 
