        title: "07 Deadlocks", 
        readTime: 20, 
        content: "# Chapter 7: Deadlocks\n\nA **Deadlock** occurs when a set of processes are blocked, each holding a resource and waiting for a resource held by another process in the set.\n\n## The 4 Coffman Conditions (ALL must hold simultaneously)\n\n1. **Mutual Exclusion**: At least one resource is non-shareable (only one process can use it at a time).\n2. **Hold and Wait**: A process holds at least one resource and waits for additional resources held by others.\n3. **No Preemption**: Resources cannot be forcibly taken from a process; they must be released voluntarily.\n4. **Circular Wait**: A circular chain of processes exists, each waiting for a resource held by the next.\n\n## Resource Allocation Graph (RAG)\n\n```\nProcess Pi ──(request)──> Resource Rj\nResource Rj ──(assignment)──> Process Pi\n\nDeadlock exists if and only if the RAG contains a CYCLE\n(when each resource has only one instance)\n```\n\n## Deadlock Handling Strategies\n\n### 1. Deadlock Prevention\nBreak at least ONE of the 4 conditions:\n- **Break Hold & Wait**: Require processes to request ALL resources at once before execution.\n- **Break No Preemption**: If a process cannot get all resources, release what it holds.\n- **Break Circular Wait**: Impose a total ordering on resources. Process must request in increasing order.\n\n### 2. Deadlock Avoidance — Banker's Algorithm\nThe OS checks if granting a request leads to a **safe state** (a sequence exists where all processes can complete).\n\n**Banker's Algorithm Example:**\n```\nProcesses: P0, P1, P2, P3\nResources: A(10), B(5), C(7)\n\nAllocation    Max        Need (Max-Alloc)   Available\nP0: 0 1 0    7 5 3      7 4 3              3 3 2\nP1: 2 0 0    3 2 2      1 2 2\nP2: 3 0 2    9 0 2      6 0 0\nP3: 2 1 1    2 2 2      0 1 1\n\nSafe Sequence: P1 → P3 → P0 → P2 ✓\n```\n\n### 3. Deadlock Detection & Recovery\nAllow deadlocks to occur, then detect and recover:\n- **Detection**: Periodically check for cycles in the resource allocation graph.\n- **Recovery**: Kill one or more processes, or preempt resources.\n\n### 4. Deadlock Ignorance (Ostrich Algorithm)\nJust ignore the problem. Used by most general-purpose OS (Linux, Windows) because deadlocks are rare and prevention/avoidance is expensive.\n\n## FAANG Interview Questions:\n- What are the 4 conditions for deadlock?\n- Explain the Banker's Algorithm with an example.\n- How would you prevent deadlock in a database?\n- Real-world deadlock: Two threads each holding a lock and waiting for the other's lock." 
