        title: "08 File Systems & I/O", 
        readTime: 18, 
        content: "# Chapter 8: File Systems and I/O Management\n\nThe file system provides a logical view of data storage, abstracting the complexity of disk hardware.\n\n## File System Architecture\n\n```\nUser Application\n      ↓\nLogical File System (metadata, permissions)\n      ↓\nFile Organization Module (logical blocks → physical blocks)\n      ↓\nBasic File System (block read/write commands)\n      ↓\nI/O Control (device drivers)\n      ↓\nHardware (HDD/SSD)\n```\n\n## File Allocation Methods\n\n### 1. Contiguous Allocation:\n- File occupies contiguous blocks on disk.\n- **Pros**: Simple, fast sequential and random access.\n- **Cons**: External fragmentation, file size must be known in advance.\n\n### 2. Linked Allocation:\n- Each block contains a pointer to the next block.\n- **Pros**: No external fragmentation, files can grow dynamically.\n- **Cons**: No random access (must traverse from start), pointer overhead.\n- **FAT (File Allocation Table)**: An improved version where pointers are in a separate table.\n\n### 3. Indexed Allocation (Inode-based):\n- Each file has an **index block (inode)** containing pointers to all its data blocks.\n- **Pros**: Supports random access, no external fragmentation.\n- **Cons**: Overhead for small files, index block can run out of space.\n- **Multi-level index**: Inode has direct pointers + single indirect + double indirect + triple indirect.\n\n## Inode Structure (UNIX/Linux)\n```\nInode:\n├── File metadata (size, permissions, timestamps)\n├── 12 Direct pointers → data blocks (48KB with 4KB blocks)\n├── 1 Single indirect → pointer block → data blocks\n├── 1 Double indirect → pointer block → pointer block → data blocks\n└── 1 Triple indirect → 3 levels of pointer blocks\n```\n\n## Disk Scheduling Algorithms\n\n- **FCFS**: Process requests in arrival order. Simple but high seek time.\n- **SSTF (Shortest Seek Time First)**: Move to nearest request. Risk of starvation.\n- **SCAN (Elevator)**: Move in one direction servicing requests, then reverse. Fair.\n- **C-SCAN**: Like SCAN but only services in one direction, then jumps back.\n- **LOOK/C-LOOK**: Like SCAN/C-SCAN but reverses at the last request, not the disk end.\n\n## RAID Levels\n\n- **RAID 0 (Striping)**: Data split across disks. Fast I/O but NO redundancy.\n- **RAID 1 (Mirroring)**: Data duplicated on another disk. Full redundancy but double storage.\n- **RAID 5 (Parity)**: Data and parity distributed across 3+ disks. Good balance of performance and redundancy.\n- **RAID 10 (1+0)**: Mirrored stripes. Best performance + redundancy but expensive.\n\n## FAANG Interview Questions:\n- How does the Linux inode system work?\n- Compare contiguous vs indexed allocation.\n- Explain RAID levels and their trade-offs.\n- What happens when you type `rm file.txt`? (Unlinks inode, decrements reference count)" 
