        title: "01 DBMS Architecture & ACID", 
        readTime: 20, 
        content: "# Chapter 1: DBMS Architecture & ACID Properties\n\nA **Database Management System** provides a systematic way to create, retrieve, update, and manage data. It ensures data integrity, security, and concurrent access.\n\n## 3-Schema Architecture\n\n```\nExternal Level (User Views)\n      ↓  External/Conceptual mapping\nConceptual Level (Logical Schema)\n      ↓  Conceptual/Internal mapping\nInternal Level (Physical Storage)\n```\n\n- **External Level**: Different views for different users (e.g., HR sees employee data, Finance sees salary data).\n- **Conceptual Level**: Overall logical structure of the entire database (entities, relationships, constraints).\n- **Internal Level**: How data is physically stored (indexes, file organization, storage allocation).\n\n**Data Independence**: Ability to change one level without affecting others.\n- **Logical Data Independence**: Change conceptual schema without changing external views.\n- **Physical Data Independence**: Change internal schema without changing conceptual schema.\n\n## ACID Properties (Transaction Guarantee)\n\n### Atomicity (All or Nothing)\nA transaction either completes fully or not at all. If a bank transfer debits Account A but crashes before crediting Account B, the entire transaction is rolled back.\n- **Implementation**: Write-Ahead Logging (WAL). All changes are logged BEFORE being applied.\n\n### Consistency\nA transaction brings the database from one consistent state to another. All integrity constraints (primary keys, foreign keys, check constraints) must hold after the transaction.\n\n### Isolation\nConcurrent transactions should not interfere with each other. Each transaction should feel like it's the only one running.\n\n**Isolation Levels (from weakest to strongest):**\n\n| Level | Dirty Read | Non-Repeatable Read | Phantom Read |\n|-------|-----------|--------------------|--------------|\n| Read Uncommitted | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |\n| Read Committed | ❌ No | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |\n| Repeatable Read | ❌ No | ❌ No | ✅ Yes |\n| Serializable | ❌ No | ❌ No | ❌ No |\n\n- **Dirty Read**: Reading data modified by an uncommitted transaction.\n- **Non-Repeatable Read**: Reading the same row twice gives different values (another transaction modified it).\n- **Phantom Read**: Re-executing a query returns new rows (another transaction inserted them).\n\n### Durability\nOnce a transaction is committed, its changes survive even system crashes. Ensured by writing to non-volatile storage (disk).\n\n## Keys in DBMS\n\n- **Super Key**: Any set of attributes that uniquely identifies a tuple.\n- **Candidate Key**: Minimal super key (no proper subset is a super key).\n- **Primary Key**: Chosen candidate key for the table.\n- **Foreign Key**: Attribute that references the primary key of another table.\n- **Composite Key**: Primary key made of multiple columns.\n\n## FAANG Interview Questions:\n- Explain all 4 ACID properties with real-world examples.\n- What are the different isolation levels? Which does your DB use by default?\n- What is data independence? Why is it important?\n- Difference between DBMS and RDBMS?" 
