        title: "02 ER Model & Data Models", 
        readTime: 18, 
        content: "# Chapter 2: ER Model & Relational Data Model\n\n## Entity-Relationship (ER) Model\n\nThe ER model is used for conceptual database design. It describes data in terms of entities, attributes, and relationships.\n\n### Core Concepts:\n\n- **Entity**: A real-world object (Student, Course, Employee). Represented as a rectangle.\n- **Attribute**: A property of an entity (Name, Age, ID). Represented as an oval.\n  - **Simple**: Cannot be divided (Name).\n  - **Composite**: Can be divided (FullName → FirstName + LastName).\n  - **Derived**: Computed from other attributes (Age from DOB).\n  - **Multi-valued**: Can have multiple values (PhoneNumbers).\n  - **Key Attribute**: Uniquely identifies an entity (StudentID). Underlined.\n\n- **Relationship**: Association between entities (Student ENROLLS_IN Course).\n  - **Degree**: Unary (1 entity), Binary (2 entities), Ternary (3 entities).\n\n### Cardinality Constraints:\n- **1:1** (One-to-One): Person HAS Passport.\n- **1:N** (One-to-Many): Department HAS Employees.\n- **M:N** (Many-to-Many): Students ENROLL_IN Courses.\n\n### Participation:\n- **Total Participation**: Every entity must participate (double line). Example: Every employee WORKS_IN a department.\n- **Partial Participation**: Some entities may not participate (single line). Example: Not every employee MANAGES a department.\n\n## Relational Model\n\n### Converting ER to Relational Schema:\n\n1. **Strong Entity** → Table with all attributes.\n2. **Weak Entity** → Table with partial key + owner's primary key.\n3. **1:1 Relationship** → Add foreign key to either table (preferring total participation side).\n4. **1:N Relationship** → Add foreign key on the 'N' side.\n5. **M:N Relationship** → Create a new junction table with both primary keys.\n\n### Relational Algebra (Query Language):\n- **σ (Selection)**: Filter rows. σ(salary > 50000)(Employee)\n- **π (Projection)**: Select columns. π(name, salary)(Employee)\n- **⋈ (Join)**: Combine tables on common attribute.\n- **∪ (Union)**: Combine compatible tables.\n- **- (Difference)**: Rows in one table but not another.\n- **× (Cartesian Product)**: All combinations of rows.\n\n## FAANG Interview Questions:\n- Design an ER diagram for a library management system.\n- How do you convert M:N relationship to tables?\n- What is a weak entity? Give an example.\n- Write relational algebra for: 'Find names of employees earning > 50K'" 
