        title: "01 Introduction to OOPs", 
        readTime: 15, 
        content: "# Chapter 1: Introduction to Object-Oriented Programming\n\nOOP is a programming paradigm based on the concept of 'objects' that contain data (attributes) and code (methods).\n\n## Why OOPs?\n\nProcedural programming (C-style) becomes unmanageable for large systems. OOP solves this through:\n\n- **Modularity**: Code is organized into self-contained objects.\n- **Reusability**: Classes can be reused across projects.\n- **Extensibility**: New functionality via inheritance without modifying existing code.\n- **Maintainability**: Changes to one object don't break others.\n\n## Classes and Objects\n\n- **Class**: A blueprint/template defining attributes and methods.\n- **Object**: An instance of a class with actual values.\n\n```\nClass: Car\n  Attributes: brand, color, speed\n  Methods: accelerate(), brake(), turn()\n\nObject: myCar = new Car('Tesla', 'Red', 0)\n```\n\n## Core Concepts:\n\n### Access Modifiers:\n- **private**: Only accessible within the class.\n- **protected**: Accessible within the class and subclasses.\n- **public**: Accessible from anywhere.\n- **default (package-private)**: Accessible within the same package (Java-specific).\n\n### Static vs Instance:\n- **Instance members**: Belong to objects. Each object has its own copy.\n- **Static members**: Belong to the class. Shared across all objects. Only one copy in memory.\n\n### Constructors:\n- Special method called when an object is created.\n- Same name as the class, no return type.\n- **Default Constructor**: No parameters, initializes defaults.\n- **Parameterized Constructor**: Takes arguments to initialize.\n- **Copy Constructor**: Creates a new object as a copy of an existing one.\n\n### Destructor / Finalizer:\n- Called when object is destroyed / garbage collected.\n- In Java: `finalize()` (deprecated). In C++: `~ClassName()`.\n- In modern Java: Use `try-with-resources` or `AutoCloseable`.\n\n## OOP vs Procedural vs Functional:\n\n| Aspect | OOP | Procedural | Functional |\n|--------|-----|-----------|------------|\n| Unit | Object | Function | Pure Function |\n| State | Mutable | Mutable | Immutable |\n| Focus | Data + Behavior | Steps | Transformations |\n| Examples | Java, C++ | C, Pascal | Haskell, Elixir |\n\n## FAANG Interview Questions:\n- What is the difference between a class and an object?\n- What are access modifiers? When to use each?\n- Explain static vs instance members with examples.\n- What is a copy constructor? When would you use one?" 
