        title: "04 Design Patterns & Advanced OOPs", 
        readTime: 22, 
        content: "# Chapter 4: Design Patterns & Advanced Concepts\n\n## Creational Patterns\n\n### Singleton:\nExactly one instance of a class exists globally.\n```java\npublic class Logger {\n    private static volatile Logger instance;\n    private Logger() { }  // Private constructor\n\n    public static Logger getInstance() {\n        if (instance == null) {\n            synchronized (Logger.class) {\n                if (instance == null) {\n                    instance = new Logger();\n                }\n            }\n        }\n        return instance;\n    }\n}\n```\n**Thread-safe** via double-checked locking + `volatile`.\n\n### Factory Method:\nDefine an interface for creating objects, let subclasses decide which class to instantiate.\n```java\ninterface Notification { void send(String msg); }\nclass EmailNotification implements Notification { ... }\nclass SMSNotification implements Notification { ... }\n\nclass NotificationFactory {\n    static Notification create(String type) {\n        return switch(type) {\n            case \"email\" -> new EmailNotification();\n            case \"sms\" -> new SMSNotification();\n            default -> throw new IllegalArgumentException();\n        };\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Builder:\nConstruct complex objects step-by-step.\n```java\nUser user = new User.Builder()\n    .name(\"Prateek\")\n    .email(\"p@test.com\")\n    .age(25)\n    .build();\n```\n\n## Structural Patterns\n\n### Adapter:\nMake incompatible interfaces work together.\n- **Real-world**: Power adapter (US plug → EU socket).\n\n### Decorator:\nAdd functionality dynamically without modifying the original.\n```java\n// Java I/O uses Decorator pattern\nnew BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(new FileInputStream(\"file.txt\")));\n```\n\n## Behavioral Patterns\n\n### Observer:\nOne-to-many dependency. When one object changes state, all dependents are notified.\n- **Real-world**: YouTube subscriptions. When a channel uploads, all subscribers are notified.\n\n### Strategy:\nDefine a family of algorithms, encapsulate each one, and make them interchangeable.\n```java\ninterface SortStrategy { void sort(int[] arr); }\nclass QuickSort implements SortStrategy { ... }\nclass MergeSort implements SortStrategy { ... }\n\nclass Sorter {\n    private SortStrategy strategy;\n    void setStrategy(SortStrategy s) { strategy = s; }\n    void sort(int[] arr) { strategy.sort(arr); }\n}\n```\n\n## Advanced Concepts\n\n### Composition vs Inheritance:\n- **Inheritance**: IS-A relationship (Dog IS-A Animal).\n- **Composition**: HAS-A relationship (Car HAS-A Engine).\n- **Rule**: Favor composition over inheritance. Inheritance creates tight coupling.\n\n### Association, Aggregation, Composition:\n- **Association**: 'Uses' (Teacher uses Marker).\n- **Aggregation**: 'Has' with independent lifecycle (Department has Employees — employees exist without department).\n- **Composition**: 'Has' with dependent lifecycle (House has Rooms — rooms don't exist without house).\n\n### Coupling vs Cohesion:\n- **Low Coupling** (GOOD): Classes are independent of each other.\n- **High Cohesion** (GOOD): A class's methods are closely related to its purpose.\n\n## FAANG Interview Questions:\n- Implement Singleton (thread-safe) in Java.\n- When would you use Factory vs Builder pattern?\n- Explain Observer pattern. Where is it used in real systems?\n- Composition vs Inheritance — which do you prefer and why?\n- Design a notification system using Strategy pattern." 
