        content: "# Chapter 1: SQL Fundamentals\n\nSQL (Structured Query Language) is the standard language for interacting with relational databases.\n\n## SQL Command Categories\n\n### DDL (Data Definition Language):\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE employees (\n    id INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,\n    name VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,\n    email VARCHAR(255) UNIQUE,\n    department_id INT,\n    salary DECIMAL(10,2) DEFAULT 0,\n    hire_date DATE NOT NULL,\n    FOREIGN KEY (department_id) REFERENCES departments(id)\n);\n\nALTER TABLE employees ADD COLUMN age INT;\nALTER TABLE employees DROP COLUMN age;\nDROP TABLE employees;  -- Deletes table and data\nTRUNCATE TABLE employees;  -- Deletes all data, keeps structure\n```\n\n### DML (Data Manipulation Language):\n```sql\n-- INSERT\nINSERT INTO employees (name, email, salary)\nVALUES ('Prateek', 'p@test.com', 85000);\n\n-- UPDATE\nUPDATE employees SET salary = salary * 1.10\nWHERE department_id = 1;\n\n-- DELETE\nDELETE FROM employees WHERE id = 5;\n```\n\n### DQL (Data Query Language):\n```sql\nSELECT name, salary\nFROM employees\nWHERE salary > 50000\nORDER BY salary DESC\nLIMIT 10;\n```\n\n### DCL (Data Control Language):\n```sql\nGRANT SELECT, INSERT ON employees TO 'analyst';\nREVOKE DELETE ON employees FROM 'analyst';\n```\n\n### TCL (Transaction Control Language):\n```sql\nBEGIN TRANSACTION;\nUPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 1000 WHERE id = 1;\nUPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 1000 WHERE id = 2;\nCOMMIT;  -- or ROLLBACK;\n```\n\n## SQL Execution Order\n\n```\nFROM → WHERE → GROUP BY → HAVING → SELECT → ORDER BY → LIMIT\n```\nThis is different from the writing order! Understanding this helps debug queries.\n\n## Constraints:\n- **PRIMARY KEY**: Unique + NOT NULL identifier.\n- **FOREIGN KEY**: References primary key of another table.\n- **UNIQUE**: No duplicate values (allows one NULL).\n- **NOT NULL**: Cannot be NULL.\n- **CHECK**: Custom validation (CHECK salary > 0).\n- **DEFAULT**: Default value if none specified.\n\n## FAANG Interview Questions:\n- What is the difference between DELETE, DROP, and TRUNCATE?\n- What is the order of execution of a SQL query?\n- What is the difference between HAVING and WHERE?\n- Write a query to find the second highest salary." 
