        title: "04 Window Functions & Query Optimization", 
        readTime: 25, 
        content: "# Chapter 4: Window Functions & Query Optimization\n\nWindow functions perform calculations across a set of rows related to the current row WITHOUT collapsing them into groups.\n\n## Window Functions\n\n### ROW_NUMBER(), RANK(), DENSE_RANK():\n```sql\nSELECT name, department_id, salary,\n    ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY department_id ORDER BY salary DESC) as row_num,\n    RANK()       OVER (PARTITION BY department_id ORDER BY salary DESC) as rank,\n    DENSE_RANK() OVER (PARTITION BY department_id ORDER BY salary DESC) as dense_rank\nFROM employees;\n\n-- Difference:\n-- Salaries: 100, 100, 90, 80\n-- ROW_NUMBER: 1, 2, 3, 4  (always unique)\n-- RANK:       1, 1, 3, 4  (skips after tie)\n-- DENSE_RANK: 1, 1, 2, 3  (no skip after tie)\n```\n\n### LAG() and LEAD():\nAccess data from previous/next rows.\n```sql\n-- Compare each employee's salary with previous hire\nSELECT name, salary,\n    LAG(salary)  OVER (ORDER BY hire_date) as prev_salary,\n    LEAD(salary) OVER (ORDER BY hire_date) as next_salary\nFROM employees;\n```\n\n### Running Totals:\n```sql\nSELECT date, revenue,\n    SUM(revenue) OVER (ORDER BY date) as running_total,\n    AVG(revenue) OVER (ORDER BY date ROWS BETWEEN 6 PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW) as moving_avg_7d\nFROM daily_revenue;\n```\n\n### Top N per Group:\n```sql\n-- Top 3 earners per department\nWITH ranked AS (\n    SELECT name, department_id, salary,\n        DENSE_RANK() OVER (PARTITION BY department_id ORDER BY salary DESC) as rnk\n    FROM employees\n)\nSELECT * FROM ranked WHERE rnk <= 3;\n```\n\n## Query Optimization\n\n### EXPLAIN / EXPLAIN ANALYZE:\n```sql\nEXPLAIN ANALYZE\nSELECT * FROM employees WHERE email = 'test@test.com';\n\n-- Check for:\n-- Seq Scan (bad on large tables) → Need an INDEX\n-- Index Scan (good)\n-- Rows examined vs rows returned (high ratio = inefficient)\n```\n\n### Indexing Strategy:\n```sql\n-- Create indexes on frequently searched columns\nCREATE INDEX idx_emp_email ON employees(email);\nCREATE INDEX idx_emp_dept_salary ON employees(department_id, salary);\n\n-- When indexes DON'T help:\n-- Small tables (full scan is fine)\n-- Columns with low cardinality (gender: M/F)\n-- Very frequent writes (index maintenance overhead)\n```\n\n### Optimization Tips:\n1. **SELECT only needed columns** (avoid SELECT *).\n2. **Use WHERE to filter early**.\n3. **Avoid functions on indexed columns**: WHERE YEAR(date) = 2024 → can't use index. Use: WHERE date >= '2024-01-01'.\n4. **Use EXISTS instead of IN** for subqueries on large datasets.\n5. **LIMIT early** in exploratory queries.\n6. **Avoid LIKE '%search%'** — cannot use index. Use full-text search instead.\n7. **Use prepared statements** — prevents SQL injection AND allows query plan caching.\n\n### Query Execution Plan:\n```\nSELECT → Project\nFROM → Scan / Seek\nJOIN → Nested Loop / Hash Join / Merge Join\nWHERE → Filter\nGROUP BY → Hash Aggregate / Sort Aggregate\nORDER BY → Sort\nLIMIT → Top\n```\n\n## FAANG Interview Questions:\n- Explain ROW_NUMBER vs RANK vs DENSE_RANK.\n- Write a query to find the Nth highest salary per department.\n- How do you optimize a slow query?\n- What is the difference between a covering index and a composite index?\n- When would you NOT use an index?" 
